So, here we have a cover
to an issue that came

00:11:10.836 --> 00:11:14.016 A:middle
out just a year ago, but you
see that's someone different

00:11:14.016 --> 00:11:14.726 A:middle
in the suit, right?

00:11:14.896 --> 00:11:17.866 A:middle
So, you see above the Captain
America name, Sam Wilson,

00:11:18.356 --> 00:11:21.066 A:middle
The Falcon, who you may
know from the films;

00:11:21.066 --> 00:11:23.036 A:middle
from Captain America
Winter Soldier,

00:11:23.036 --> 00:11:24.276 A:middle
Captain America Civil War.

00:11:24.276 --> 00:11:28.176 A:middle
In the comic books
he was Cap's partner.

00:11:29.086 --> 00:11:31.266 A:middle
In fact there was a time,
for about 50 issues,

00:11:31.266 --> 00:11:34.606 A:middle
where they changed the name
of the comic book and it went

00:11:34.606 --> 00:11:37.246 A:middle
from being Captain America to
Captain America and Falcon.

00:11:38.166 --> 00:11:41.526 A:middle
And I know for me as a young
boy, to see a white man

00:11:41.526 --> 00:11:45.396 A:middle
and a black man, from
different backgrounds as equals,

00:11:45.396 --> 00:11:48.176 A:middle
working together, that
had an effect on me.

00:11:48.936 --> 00:11:50.136 A:middle
So, we recently did a story

00:11:50.136 --> 00:11:53.896 A:middle
where Steve's Super Soldier
Serum was running out,

00:11:54.576 --> 00:12:00.216 A:middle
and he said to Sam, America
still needs a Captain America.

00:11:54.576 --> 00:12:00.216 A:middle
and he said to Sam, America
still needs a Captain America.

00:12:00.576 --> 00:12:01.796 A:middle
Will you take the shield?

00:12:02.766 --> 00:12:03.786 A:middle
Will you take over for me?

00:12:04.756 --> 00:12:06.516 A:middle
And we did -- and he said, yes.

00:12:06.796 --> 00:12:10.426 A:middle
We published this, and of
course we had some reactions.

00:12:10.456 --> 00:12:13.636 A:middle
People were not happy,
and we get it.

00:12:14.136 --> 00:12:15.626 A:middle
People feel -- why
are you messing

00:12:15.696 --> 00:12:16.946 A:middle
around with my character?

00:12:17.476 --> 00:12:18.386 A:middle
You know, you're ruining them.

00:12:18.386 --> 00:12:19.586 A:middle
Why are you changing thing?

00:12:20.146 --> 00:12:21.876 A:middle
And we even get people
saying, you know,

00:12:21.876 --> 00:12:23.886 A:middle
why have you turned
Captain America black?

00:12:24.696 --> 00:12:28.686 A:middle
And we had to say, well we
didn't turn Steve Rogers a

00:12:28.686 --> 00:12:31.006 A:middle
different -- make him
into a different race.

00:12:31.006 --> 00:12:34.346 A:middle
This is actually Sam
Wilson, and he's earned this.

00:12:34.756 --> 00:12:36.266 A:middle
He's stood behind
Captain America,

00:12:36.266 --> 00:12:38.036 A:middle
and with him, for decades.

00:12:38.036 --> 00:12:41.336 A:middle
He deserves his chance
to be Captain America.

00:12:42.356 --> 00:12:44.486 A:middle
Now why did we do this?

00:12:44.486 --> 00:12:47.206 A:middle
Well, we like to try different
things with our characters

00:12:47.206 --> 00:12:49.556 A:middle
and stretch the brand
and push the brand,

00:12:49.696 --> 00:12:51.436 A:middle
but we also like to say things.

00:12:52.006 --> 00:12:54.116 A:middle
So, I'm just thinking
in my mind,

00:12:54.116 --> 00:12:56.246 A:middle
and I don't know exactly what
the creators were saying,

00:12:56.246 --> 00:12:58.696 A:middle
but I think perhaps
they were saying

00:12:58.696 --> 00:13:02.126 A:middle
that it doesn't matter what
the color of your skin is,

00:12:58.696 --> 00:13:02.126 A:middle
that it doesn't matter what
the color of your skin is,

00:13:03.126 --> 00:13:04.216 A:middle
if you have the heart.

00:13:04.766 --> 00:13:08.656 A:middle
If you have the heart you
can be Captain America too.

00:13:10.716 --> 00:13:14.236 A:middle
My next friend, he
was also a skinny kid.

00:13:14.756 --> 00:13:18.706 A:middle
He was from Queens as well.

00:13:18.706 --> 00:13:21.936 A:middle
He was a bit of what
you would call a nerd.

00:13:22.516 --> 00:13:24.766 A:middle
He was picked on by the jocks.

00:13:25.096 --> 00:13:27.536 A:middle
See he was really into
science, my friend.

00:13:28.266 --> 00:13:30.906 A:middle
And he was an orphan
and he was raised

00:13:30.906 --> 00:13:33.246 A:middle
by an older aunt and uncle.

00:13:33.846 --> 00:13:36.006 A:middle
And he really felt the
world was against him.

00:13:36.746 --> 00:13:39.616 A:middle
And one day his uncle said
to him, hey, when you grow

00:13:39.616 --> 00:13:42.476 A:middle
up you're going to have a lot of
power because -- you're smart.

00:13:43.266 --> 00:13:44.286 A:middle
So, when you do grow

00:13:44.286 --> 00:13:47.726 A:middle
up you should use your
powers responsibly.

00:13:48.486 --> 00:13:50.746 A:middle
And my friend kind
of said, whatever.

00:13:51.476 --> 00:13:54.986 A:middle
And when he grew up and he was
a teenager he realized he was

00:13:55.076 --> 00:13:58.276 A:middle
pretty smart and he did
have some amazing abilities,

00:13:58.706 --> 00:14:02.176 A:middle
and one night he was out and
there was a cop, police officer,

00:13:58.706 --> 00:14:02.176 A:middle
and one night he was out and
there was a cop, police officer,

00:14:02.176 --> 00:14:04.556 A:middle
chasing a thief and the
cop was yelling, hey,

00:14:04.556 --> 00:14:05.646 A:middle
hey help me stop this thief.

00:14:06.106 --> 00:14:10.256 A:middle
And my friend said, from now on
I'm looking out for number one,

00:14:10.416 --> 00:14:11.746 A:middle
and he took a step back.

00:14:12.146 --> 00:14:13.366 A:middle
And that thief ran by,

00:14:13.846 --> 00:14:16.266 A:middle
and as fate would have it
two days later that thief ran

00:14:16.326 --> 00:14:19.856 A:middle
into my friend's uncle
and shot him dead.

00:14:20.306 --> 00:14:23.706 A:middle
And my friend said, if only
I'd listened to my uncle,

00:14:23.706 --> 00:14:25.686 A:middle
one of the only nice
men in my life.

00:14:26.186 --> 00:14:28.956 A:middle
If I'd listened to him
he would still be alive

00:14:29.336 --> 00:14:32.616 A:middle
and my aunt wouldn't be
devastated by his loss.

00:14:32.876 --> 00:14:36.796 A:middle
And from that moment forward,
as a dedication to his uncle,

00:14:36.796 --> 00:14:39.706 A:middle
he decided, I will use
my powers responsibly.

00:14:40.206 --> 00:14:41.206 A:middle
So, who am I talking about?

00:14:41.206 --> 00:14:44.096 A:middle
My next friend -- Spider-Man!

00:14:44.356 --> 00:14:45.936 A:middle
So, now it's 1963.

00:14:46.776 --> 00:14:48.286 A:middle
I mention that because all

00:14:48.286 --> 00:14:50.356 A:middle
of our creators were
using our comics to talk

00:14:50.356 --> 00:14:52.346 A:middle
about what's going
on around them.

00:14:52.476 --> 00:14:55.756 A:middle
And this was really the birth
of the Marvel Character.

00:14:56.446 --> 00:14:57.726 A:middle
And what do I mean by that?

00:14:57.726 --> 00:15:00.646 A:middle
Well, Spider-Man looked
a little different

00:14:57.726 --> 00:15:00.646 A:middle
Well, Spider-Man looked
a little different

00:15:00.936 --> 00:15:02.266 A:middle
than heroes that came before.

00:15:02.486 --> 00:15:04.396 A:middle
And once you start reading
his adventures you found

00:15:04.396 --> 00:15:06.416 A:middle
out he was truly different.

00:15:06.936 --> 00:15:11.346 A:middle
And his creators, Stan Lee and
Steve Ditko, they got yelled

00:15:11.346 --> 00:15:13.186 A:middle
at too when they came into work.

00:15:13.416 --> 00:15:16.406 A:middle
So, they came into work and
the publisher, Martin Goodman,

00:15:16.476 --> 00:15:18.096 A:middle
said, what are you doing?

00:15:19.066 --> 00:15:24.726 A:middle
You've published a comic with a
character named after a spider

00:15:25.306 --> 00:15:27.696 A:middle
and he has an insect
on his chest.

00:15:28.306 --> 00:15:29.796 A:middle
Everybody hates bugs.

00:15:30.846 --> 00:15:31.606 A:middle
What are you doing?

00:15:31.736 --> 00:15:32.816 A:middle
And you've covered his face.

00:15:32.816 --> 00:15:34.506 A:middle
He looks like a bank robber.

00:15:34.506 --> 00:15:35.706 A:middle
We can't see his face.

00:15:36.156 --> 00:15:38.526 A:middle
And worst of all,
he's a teenager!

00:15:39.336 --> 00:15:41.016 A:middle
Teenagers should be sidekicks.

00:15:41.516 --> 00:15:43.416 A:middle
Who wants to read
about a teenager?

00:15:44.376 --> 00:15:45.646 A:middle
Well, the new generation did.

00:15:46.476 --> 00:15:48.876 A:middle
So, the greatest generation
is back from World War II.

00:15:48.916 --> 00:15:50.106 A:middle
It's 20 years later.

00:15:50.106 --> 00:15:52.266 A:middle
It's the rise of
the teenage culture.

00:15:52.736 --> 00:15:54.096 A:middle
They have disposable income.

00:15:54.436 --> 00:15:56.116 A:middle
They want to read about
heroes that are different.

00:15:56.116 --> 00:15:58.056 A:middle
They want to read about
heroes that are like them.

00:15:58.716 --> 00:15:59.786 A:middle
They want to read about heroes

00:15:59.786 --> 00:16:02.996 A:middle
that are a little more
relatable, who are not perfect,

00:15:59.786 --> 00:16:02.996 A:middle
that are a little more
relatable, who are not perfect,

00:16:03.326 --> 00:16:05.876 A:middle
they're not square jawed
aliens from another world,

00:16:05.876 --> 00:16:08.836 A:middle
or rich billionaires, they
are skinny Peter Parker

00:16:08.836 --> 00:16:10.636 A:middle
from Queens who gets picked on.

00:16:11.186 --> 00:16:14.466 A:middle
But the publisher
didn't realize this,

00:16:14.856 --> 00:16:17.336 A:middle
didn't know who was
going to read this book.

00:16:17.336 --> 00:16:19.096 A:middle
And so he's yelling
at Stan and Steve,

00:16:19.426 --> 00:16:20.576 A:middle
what the hell are you doing?

00:16:22.156 --> 00:16:24.926 A:middle
As you can guess, at that moment
in comes someone from sales.

00:16:25.226 --> 00:16:27.886 A:middle
Boss, boss, look at
the sales numbers!

00:16:29.226 --> 00:16:30.926 A:middle
Keep doing it!

00:16:31.556 --> 00:16:32.196 A:middle
Another hit.

00:16:32.346 --> 00:16:36.406 A:middle
And you can see what made
him really different.

00:16:36.406 --> 00:16:40.576 A:middle
I mean check out poor Peter
over there in the bow tie,

00:16:40.726 --> 00:16:43.946 A:middle
and the glasses, and the kids
pointing at him, and laughing

00:16:43.946 --> 00:16:48.166 A:middle
at him, and as you can see, via
the art, without reading a word,

00:16:48.166 --> 00:16:49.866 A:middle
you see that he's ostracized.

00:16:50.176 --> 00:16:51.326 A:middle
He feels alone.

00:16:51.596 --> 00:16:52.826 A:middle
He is an underdog.

00:16:53.276 --> 00:16:54.126 A:middle
But look behind him.

00:16:55.006 --> 00:16:57.406 A:middle
Look at the shadow
of the hero within.

00:16:57.406 --> 00:17:01.456 A:middle
And don't we all feel
that way sometimes.

00:16:57.406 --> 00:17:01.456 A:middle
And don't we all feel
that way sometimes.

00:17:01.746 --> 00:17:03.866 A:middle
We feel the world is against us.

00:17:03.866 --> 00:17:08.506 A:middle
We feel the world is judging us,
but we know, we know within us,

00:17:08.955 --> 00:17:12.236 A:middle
if given the opportunity,
lies greatness.

00:17:14.356 --> 00:17:16.056 A:middle
So, as with Captain America,

00:17:16.356 --> 00:17:17.965 A:middle
Spider-Man was a
bit controversial

00:17:17.965 --> 00:17:19.496 A:middle
when he came out,
with some readers.

00:17:19.496 --> 00:17:20.536 A:middle
They didn't get it.

00:17:20.715 --> 00:17:21.616 A:middle
But many more did.

00:17:21.616 --> 00:17:25.476 A:middle
And that wasn't the only
controversial things

00:17:26.126 --> 00:17:27.665 A:middle
that we did with him.

00:17:28.566 --> 00:17:33.886 A:middle
Let's see, in 1970 the president
happened to be Richard Nixon,

00:17:34.066 --> 00:17:38.036 A:middle
believe it or not, went to Stan
Lee, and President Nixon said,

00:17:38.426 --> 00:17:40.526 A:middle
Stan we have this
problem with drugs.

00:17:40.526 --> 00:17:43.266 A:middle
And we're going to lose
a lot of young people.

00:17:44.146 --> 00:17:47.466 A:middle
And President Nixon knew
how popular the comics were,

00:17:47.466 --> 00:17:48.586 A:middle
that Marvel were publishing.

00:17:48.586 --> 00:17:50.516 A:middle
And he said, could
you do a comic book

00:17:50.516 --> 00:17:53.526 A:middle
that would mention
the drug problem?

00:17:54.696 --> 00:17:56.636 A:middle
Stan thought about it and he
said, you know what, I will.

00:17:56.636 --> 00:18:01.086 A:middle
And what was remarkable
is he did it in the pages

00:17:56.636 --> 00:18:01.086 A:middle
And what was remarkable
is he did it in the pages

00:18:01.086 --> 00:18:02.256 A:middle
of Amazing Spider-Man.

00:18:02.766 --> 00:18:05.586 A:middle
Now we had many characters
to choose from.

00:18:05.746 --> 00:18:07.206 A:middle
Stan could have selected one

00:18:07.206 --> 00:18:09.036 A:middle
of our less popular
characters, but he didn't.

00:18:09.596 --> 00:18:10.416 A:middle
He picked Spider-Man.

00:18:10.416 --> 00:18:12.666 A:middle
Now, you'll see there's
something that's not

00:18:12.666 --> 00:18:14.036 A:middle
on this cover.

00:18:14.596 --> 00:18:19.166 A:middle
Now see up there on the top
right of Amazing Fantasy 15.

00:18:19.166 --> 00:18:20.986 A:middle
That's the Comic's
Code Authority Stamp,

00:18:21.496 --> 00:18:23.736 A:middle
was a seal of approval
that basically told parents

00:18:23.736 --> 00:18:26.836 A:middle
that the comic was safe for
younger readers to read,

00:18:26.836 --> 00:18:29.166 A:middle
it didn't have, you
know certain levels

00:18:29.166 --> 00:18:31.396 A:middle
of violence, things like that.

00:18:31.926 --> 00:18:34.426 A:middle
What's not on this cover?

00:18:34.426 --> 00:18:35.386 A:middle
There's no Comic's Code.

00:18:35.506 --> 00:18:37.516 A:middle
See what happened was,
when we were ready

00:18:37.516 --> 00:18:39.466 A:middle
to publish it Stan
gave the comic

00:18:39.466 --> 00:18:42.356 A:middle
to the Comic's Code Authority
to read and to give their stamp

00:18:42.356 --> 00:18:45.326 A:middle
of approval and the Comic's Code
said, you can't publish this.

00:18:46.036 --> 00:18:47.296 A:middle
Stan said, why not?

00:18:47.996 --> 00:18:49.496 A:middle
He said because it
mentions drugs.

00:18:49.846 --> 00:18:52.826 A:middle
Stan said, but it's not
doing it in a positive way.

00:18:52.826 --> 00:18:54.286 A:middle
It's an antidrug story.

00:18:54.286 --> 00:18:55.246 A:middle
And they said, we don't care.

00:18:55.866 --> 00:18:58.736 A:middle
You -- the Comic's Code says
there can be no mention of drugs

00:18:58.966 --> 00:19:01.356 A:middle
in the comic, so you
can't publish this

00:18:58.966 --> 00:19:01.356 A:middle
in the comic, so you
can't publish this

00:19:01.356 --> 00:19:03.366 A:middle
with the Comic's Code
Stamp of Approval.

00:19:03.586 --> 00:19:06.766 A:middle
And Stan said, good, we're
going to publish it anyway;

00:19:07.136 --> 00:19:08.006 A:middle
without the Comic's Code.

00:19:09.136 --> 00:19:13.896 A:middle
First time that happened,
and it was a hit.

00:19:14.706 --> 00:19:16.066 A:middle
People really responded to it.

00:19:16.466 --> 00:19:21.036 A:middle
They responded to, really kind
of a smart, difficult story.

00:19:21.036 --> 00:19:23.906 A:middle
In the story Peter's
roommate, Harry Osborn,

00:19:23.906 --> 00:19:27.016 A:middle
the son of the Green
Goblin, had a pill problem,

00:19:27.776 --> 00:19:30.386 A:middle
and Spider-Man had to council
him and finally get him help.

00:19:30.386 --> 00:19:32.816 A:middle
But they handled it in
a way that the readers

00:19:32.816 --> 00:19:34.176 A:middle
at the time could appreciate.

00:19:34.896 --> 00:19:37.606 A:middle
Stan was really speaking to
the readers in a language

00:19:37.606 --> 00:19:38.526 A:middle
that they wanted to hear.

00:19:39.366 --> 00:19:42.016 A:middle
But, as you can guess, it
was a little controversial,

00:19:42.016 --> 00:19:43.996 A:middle
but sometimes we've
got to take a stand.

00:19:44.036 --> 00:19:47.296 A:middle
Right? We have to use
art to send a message.

00:19:47.666 --> 00:19:50.066 A:middle
But it didn't stop
there, with that issue.

00:19:50.066 --> 00:19:54.196 A:middle
No. We use Spider-Man
from time to time

00:19:54.496 --> 00:19:55.496 A:middle
to speak to other things.

00:19:55.496 --> 00:19:58.696 A:middle
So, in this case it was
2011, and we had a line

00:19:58.696 --> 00:20:01.926 A:middle
of comics called The Ultimate
Line of Marvel Comics.

00:19:58.696 --> 00:20:01.926 A:middle
of comics called The Ultimate
Line of Marvel Comics.

00:20:01.926 --> 00:20:03.926 A:middle
They were set on another
world where we kind

00:20:03.926 --> 00:20:05.626 A:middle
of started -- we started now.

00:20:06.066 --> 00:20:08.006 A:middle
Rather than having our
history starting in the 60s,

00:20:08.006 --> 00:20:09.366 A:middle
we kind of started
this new line,

00:20:09.366 --> 00:20:10.646 A:middle
but wanted to make it different.

00:20:10.706 --> 00:20:12.356 A:middle
We wanted to make it unexpected.

00:20:12.356 --> 00:20:16.726 A:middle
And so actually on that
world that Peter Parker died

00:20:16.936 --> 00:20:20.926 A:middle
in battle protecting Aunt
May from the Green Goblin.

00:20:21.326 --> 00:20:25.466 A:middle
And in that reality there was
a boy named Miles Morales,

00:20:26.216 --> 00:20:30.126 A:middle
who happened to also be
infected by a spider bite.

00:20:30.696 --> 00:20:33.776 A:middle
And when that world's Peter
Parker died Miles decided the

00:20:33.776 --> 00:20:35.556 A:middle
world still needs a Spider-Man.

00:20:35.556 --> 00:20:37.886 A:middle
So, he made his own
costume and he became

00:20:38.146 --> 00:20:41.316 A:middle
that world's Spider-Man.

00:20:41.596 --> 00:20:44.586 A:middle
And, as you can see, looks a
bit different from Peter, right?

00:20:44.986 --> 00:20:47.346 A:middle
He's half African American,
and he's half Puerto Rican.

00:20:47.686 --> 00:20:52.926 A:middle
And I remember the day I came
into work, I was an editor

00:20:53.086 --> 00:20:54.536 A:middle
at the time for Marvel
Publishing.

00:20:54.886 --> 00:20:56.366 A:middle
An editor is sort
of like a producer,

00:20:57.226 --> 00:20:59.746 A:middle
we're selecting the writers
and the artists to work

00:20:59.746 --> 00:21:02.056 A:middle
on the series, and we're working
with them through every step

00:20:59.746 --> 00:21:02.056 A:middle
on the series, and we're working
with them through every step

00:21:02.056 --> 00:21:04.626 A:middle
of the way, deciding
what's printed on the cover

00:21:04.626 --> 00:21:06.396 A:middle
to what's in the word balloons.

00:21:06.396 --> 00:21:07.266 A:middle
We work on everything.

00:21:07.266 --> 00:21:09.136 A:middle
And we also have access

00:21:09.476 --> 00:21:13.216 A:middle
to an email account
called mheros@marvel.com,

00:21:13.626 --> 00:21:15.126 A:middle
and people can write in letters.

00:21:15.976 --> 00:21:17.616 A:middle
Usually they write in and say,

00:21:18.316 --> 00:21:20.406 A:middle
why can't Peter Parker
marry Jane,

00:21:20.406 --> 00:21:22.306 A:middle
be happily married ever after?

