I lied a bit, it's
actually a group.

00:33:39.746 --> 00:33:40.676 A:middle
It's a group of friends,

00:33:40.676 --> 00:33:44.176 A:middle
but they're so united
I think of them as one.

00:33:44.766 --> 00:33:48.546 A:middle
These friends, like my
other friends, were orphaned

00:33:48.546 --> 00:33:50.816 A:middle
in some way, and
they felt alone,

00:33:50.816 --> 00:33:52.266 A:middle
and they felt like misfits.

00:33:52.776 --> 00:33:54.866 A:middle
But they ran into each
other and they looked around

00:33:54.866 --> 00:33:55.916 A:middle
and they said, you know what?

00:33:55.916 --> 00:33:57.066 A:middle
You're my kind of misfit.

00:33:57.496 --> 00:33:59.986 A:middle
And they formed a
new family together,

00:33:59.986 --> 00:34:02.806 A:middle
and they were all very
different, but they said,

00:33:59.986 --> 00:34:02.806 A:middle
and they were all very
different, but they said,

00:34:02.806 --> 00:34:04.866 A:middle
you know despite our differences
we can stand together

00:34:04.866 --> 00:34:07.236 A:middle
and we can save,
not only the world,

00:34:07.236 --> 00:34:09.755 A:middle
we can save the entire galaxy.

00:34:10.726 --> 00:34:13.386 A:middle
My next friends, The
Guardians of the Galaxy.

00:34:14.746 --> 00:34:15.775 A:middle
Now this -- Yeah!

00:34:16.786 --> 00:34:20.096 A:middle
Yes, that's a talking
raccoon and a walking tree,

00:34:20.096 --> 00:34:21.306 A:middle
that does deserve applause!

00:34:23.456 --> 00:34:28.536 A:middle
So, this cover that came out in
2008, I was actually the editor

00:34:28.536 --> 00:34:29.936 A:middle
of the series at the time.

00:34:30.216 --> 00:34:32.416 A:middle
I was asked to edit
our Cosmic Books,

00:34:32.676 --> 00:34:34.235 A:middle
and I wanted to do a team book.

00:34:34.815 --> 00:34:37.255 A:middle
I had a book that was a
solo hero called Nova.

00:34:37.326 --> 00:34:40.886 A:middle
And I said, well now I want to
do a team, but I want it to be,

00:34:40.886 --> 00:34:44.376 A:middle
you know the freaks and geeks
of the Marvel Cosmic Heroes.

00:34:44.376 --> 00:34:46.735 A:middle
I want it to be a
true Marvel creation.

00:34:47.456 --> 00:34:49.906 A:middle
And then I got this name,
Guardians of the Galaxy.

00:34:50.005 --> 00:34:52.176 A:middle
There was a team in
the 70s with that name.

00:34:52.176 --> 00:34:54.585 A:middle
And we hadn't used that
name in a long time.

00:34:54.585 --> 00:34:56.626 A:middle
And I'm like, I want to use
-- this name is perfect.

00:34:56.626 --> 00:34:59.216 A:middle
You hear it and you know
instantly what they do;

00:34:59.216 --> 00:35:00.856 A:middle
they guard the galaxy.

00:34:59.216 --> 00:35:00.856 A:middle
they guard the galaxy.

00:35:01.486 --> 00:35:04.836 A:middle
So, one night I have
my official handbooks

00:35:04.836 --> 00:35:07.456 A:middle
of the Marvel Universe, they're
these encyclopedias, right?

00:35:07.536 --> 00:35:09.066 A:middle
And they -- with
these bio-entries.

00:35:09.066 --> 00:35:11.766 A:middle
And I have them open, and
I have them putting --

00:35:11.766 --> 00:35:14.536 A:middle
and I'm going through and I'm
finding all these characters

00:35:14.536 --> 00:35:16.966 A:middle
that I remember from
when I was little and --

00:35:16.966 --> 00:35:18.316 A:middle
but we haven't seen
them in a while.

00:35:18.566 --> 00:35:21.096 A:middle
So, I'm putting sticky
notes on all these pages,

00:35:21.096 --> 00:35:23.356 A:middle
and I have them spread
out on the floor.

00:35:23.586 --> 00:35:26.986 A:middle
And my wife comes in and she
says, Billy, what are you doing?

00:35:26.986 --> 00:35:28.086 A:middle
You're making a mess!

00:35:28.126 --> 00:35:31.746 A:middle
I said, honey, I'm building
Marvel's next great team,

00:35:32.106 --> 00:35:33.606 A:middle
and this is going
to be our star.

00:35:34.476 --> 00:35:37.566 A:middle
And I show her a page and
she says, is that a squirrel?

00:35:37.566 --> 00:35:39.196 A:middle
And I said, it's a raccoon!

00:35:40.746 --> 00:35:42.706 A:middle
Back in the 80s there was
a mini-series called Rocket

00:35:42.706 --> 00:35:44.696 A:middle
Raccoon that I thought
was just awesome.

00:35:45.086 --> 00:35:48.506 A:middle
I mean it was a raccoon with
a big gun and a jet pack

00:35:48.506 --> 00:35:50.596 A:middle
and a bad attitude, and
who doesn't love that?

00:35:51.076 --> 00:35:53.806 A:middle
And I thought if we just
give them the right platform,

00:35:54.066 --> 00:35:55.266 A:middle
then the world will love him.

00:35:55.506 --> 00:35:57.496 A:middle
And I just continued
on that role

00:35:57.496 --> 00:35:59.556 A:middle
and I found all these
crazy characters.

00:35:59.556 --> 00:36:05.356 A:middle
Groot, a walking tree and Drax,
this weird, big, muscular,

00:35:59.556 --> 00:36:05.356 A:middle
Groot, a walking tree and Drax,
this weird, big, muscular,

00:36:05.356 --> 00:36:08.816 A:middle
but not too smart assassin, and
Gamora, the most deadliest woman

00:36:08.816 --> 00:36:12.266 A:middle
in the galaxy, and that's
Star-Lord there holding the gun.

00:36:12.646 --> 00:36:16.676 A:middle
And it didn't have a huge
following, but the people

00:36:16.676 --> 00:36:18.386 A:middle
that read the comic
really loved it.

00:36:18.386 --> 00:36:20.756 A:middle
And I remember one
day my phone rings.

00:36:21.706 --> 00:36:25.066 A:middle
Hello. It's a friend over on the
West Coast and he's like, Bill,

00:36:25.826 --> 00:36:27.376 A:middle
the crew here in Marvel Studios,

00:36:27.846 --> 00:36:30.056 A:middle
we really like your
Cosmic Books,

00:36:30.056 --> 00:36:31.556 A:middle
especially Guardians
of the Galaxy.

00:36:31.816 --> 00:36:33.446 A:middle
I'm like, that's cool.

00:36:33.446 --> 00:36:35.176 A:middle
Cool bud, I'm glad you like it.

00:36:35.176 --> 00:36:37.906 A:middle
No, no, we really like it!

00:36:37.906 --> 00:36:39.906 A:middle
So, what does that mean?

00:36:40.406 --> 00:36:41.056 A:middle
Can't tell you, bye.

00:36:44.686 --> 00:36:46.166 A:middle
Click. Well, what do
I see months later?

00:36:47.296 --> 00:36:48.286 A:middle
The movie poster.

00:36:48.836 --> 00:36:52.786 A:middle
And I said, that's
our Guardians!

00:36:54.366 --> 00:36:56.366 A:middle
They made it about our team!

00:36:56.726 --> 00:36:58.756 A:middle
And it was remarked
about the film --

00:36:58.756 --> 00:37:02.246 A:middle
and of course it was great,
the script was fantastic,

00:36:58.756 --> 00:37:02.246 A:middle
and of course it was great,
the script was fantastic,

00:37:02.246 --> 00:37:05.246 A:middle
and the director, James Gunn,
and the cast, just beautiful,

00:37:05.536 --> 00:37:08.686 A:middle
it was awesome and --
but what was unique

00:37:08.686 --> 00:37:11.706 A:middle
about it was the
content was rather new

00:37:11.706 --> 00:37:12.806 A:middle
for a Marvel Studios movie.

00:37:12.806 --> 00:37:16.036 A:middle
Usually we look back, if
you think about Iron Man

00:37:16.116 --> 00:37:19.316 A:middle
and Captain America, we look
back at the original comics back

00:37:19.316 --> 00:37:21.996 A:middle
in the 60s and even
in Cap's case the 40s,

00:37:21.996 --> 00:37:23.836 A:middle
and we base the stories on that.

00:37:23.836 --> 00:37:25.406 A:middle
But they were basing
this content

00:37:25.456 --> 00:37:26.686 A:middle
from just a few years ago.

00:37:27.116 --> 00:37:30.136 A:middle
And it was characters that
no one knew about really.

00:37:30.136 --> 00:37:31.426 A:middle
When you see the
movie you walk in

00:37:31.426 --> 00:37:34.766 A:middle
and assume these are new created
characters, but they're not.

00:37:34.766 --> 00:37:35.706 A:middle
They're decades old.

00:37:35.706 --> 00:37:37.336 A:middle
They're from the 80s and the 70s

00:37:37.536 --> 00:37:39.016 A:middle
and even the 60s
these characters.

00:37:39.286 --> 00:37:40.046 A:middle
And they're crazy.

00:37:40.046 --> 00:37:40.916 A:middle
They're freaky, right?

00:37:40.916 --> 00:37:42.816 A:middle
They're -- it's like
a raccoon and a tree.

00:37:42.816 --> 00:37:44.706 A:middle
And people are like,
is this going to be --

00:37:44.706 --> 00:37:45.906 A:middle
I remember the headlines;
this is going

00:37:45.906 --> 00:37:47.516 A:middle
to be Marvel's first flop!

00:37:47.516 --> 00:37:48.606 A:middle
I said, no it's not!

00:37:48.606 --> 00:37:49.686 A:middle
It's going to be great!

00:37:50.276 --> 00:37:51.746 A:middle
And the reason it was a hit,

00:37:52.366 --> 00:37:55.206 A:middle
even though the characters
were crazy, and it took place

00:37:55.206 --> 00:37:57.836 A:middle
in space, they grounded
it in family.

00:37:57.836 --> 00:38:01.576 A:middle
It was all about family
from the very first scene

00:37:57.836 --> 00:38:01.576 A:middle
It was all about family
from the very first scene

00:38:01.576 --> 00:38:04.086 A:middle
when Peter Quill is
kidnapped from his parents,

00:38:04.446 --> 00:38:07.806 A:middle
all through the movie, when you
meet all the characters they

00:38:07.806 --> 00:38:09.736 A:middle
talk about how they feel
like they're the only one

00:38:09.736 --> 00:38:12.706 A:middle
of their kind, or in Drax
case he lost his family.

00:38:13.066 --> 00:38:15.916 A:middle
They were all alone, but they
looked at each other and said,

00:38:16.146 --> 00:38:18.126 A:middle
we will be each other's
new family.

00:38:18.806 --> 00:38:21.816 A:middle
Groot goes from I am
Groot, to we are Groot.

00:38:22.236 --> 00:38:23.906 A:middle
That was the message.

00:38:24.216 --> 00:38:27.656 A:middle
And I think everyone, in one way
or another, can relate to that.

00:38:27.976 --> 00:38:31.016 A:middle
As we grow up we often
move away from home.

00:38:31.226 --> 00:38:32.496 A:middle
We leave our family.

00:38:32.726 --> 00:38:33.846 A:middle
We go to school.

00:38:33.946 --> 00:38:35.006 A:middle
We get jobs.

00:38:35.496 --> 00:38:36.116 A:middle
What do we do?

00:38:36.116 --> 00:38:37.076 A:middle
We look around.

00:38:37.076 --> 00:38:39.116 A:middle
We find other misfits
like ourselves,

00:38:39.116 --> 00:38:40.916 A:middle
and we form new families.

00:38:41.296 --> 00:38:43.826 A:middle
I think that's what is at
the message of it and it was

00:38:43.826 --> 00:38:46.796 A:middle
in every scene and that's why
it was the hit that it was.

00:38:47.636 --> 00:38:50.956 A:middle
Alright, I have one more
friend to talk about.

00:38:50.956 --> 00:38:57.156 A:middle
And he is not on this cover, but
it all begins with this cover.

00:38:57.156 --> 00:39:00.176 A:middle
Let's see, so there I was,

00:38:57.156 --> 00:39:00.176 A:middle
Let's see, so there I was,

00:39:00.176 --> 00:39:03.466 A:middle
at work when I was
still on the East Coast.

00:39:03.736 --> 00:39:06.446 A:middle
And it was a February
and it was cold and rainy

00:39:06.446 --> 00:39:09.526 A:middle
and I had walked 20 minutes from
Grand Central and I was soaked.

00:39:10.086 --> 00:39:13.706 A:middle
And my phone's ringing and I
know I have to go to a meeting

00:39:13.706 --> 00:39:16.016 A:middle
in 20 minutes and I
turn on my computer

00:39:16.016 --> 00:39:17.176 A:middle
and I look at my emails.

00:39:17.176 --> 00:39:19.066 A:middle
And there's a wall,
a wall of emails.

00:39:19.766 --> 00:39:22.316 A:middle
And some of them were, like
I mentioned, that email,

00:39:22.386 --> 00:39:24.646 A:middle
mheroes@marvel.com,
letters were coming in.

00:39:25.056 --> 00:39:26.216 A:middle
And some of them were again,

00:39:26.216 --> 00:39:28.646 A:middle
saying how they loved some
issues and hated some issues.

00:39:28.916 --> 00:39:31.336 A:middle
And one subject line
just said, help.

00:39:31.336 --> 00:39:35.476 A:middle
That got my attention
so I opened the email.

00:39:35.986 --> 00:39:38.776 A:middle
And it was not a letter
complaining about Rogue

00:39:38.776 --> 00:39:40.576 A:middle
and Gambit or Peter
Parker and Mary Jane.

00:39:40.576 --> 00:39:42.416 A:middle
No, it was from a
mom named Christina.

00:39:43.866 --> 00:39:45.906 A:middle
She said, I need your help.

00:39:46.776 --> 00:39:50.616 A:middle
Said, my little boy Anthony,
who's four years old,

00:39:51.386 --> 00:39:54.166 A:middle
this morning he did not want
to wear his hearing aid.

00:39:55.116 --> 00:39:57.066 A:middle
We call it blue ear because
it's made of blue plastic.

00:39:57.396 --> 00:39:59.686 A:middle
He said, mama, I'm
not wearing blue ear.

00:40:00.466 --> 00:40:01.456 A:middle
And I said, why not?

00:40:01.656 --> 00:40:05.266 A:middle
And he said, because super
heroes don't wear blue ears.

00:40:06.416 --> 00:40:10.676 A:middle
So, Anthony at that age,
four, knew he was different.

00:40:11.846 --> 00:40:14.926 A:middle
So, Christina tells me
that she says, yes they do.

00:40:14.926 --> 00:40:16.476 A:middle
Super heroes where hearing aids.

00:40:16.476 --> 00:40:19.826 A:middle
And he said, you mean
like Marvel Characters?

00:40:20.216 --> 00:40:21.576 A:middle
And she said, yes of course.

00:40:21.576 --> 00:40:23.926 A:middle
And he said, well
mama, which ones?

00:40:23.926 --> 00:40:26.586 A:middle
She said, I'll tell you when
you get back from school.

00:40:26.586 --> 00:40:30.196 A:middle
She drives Anthony to school.

00:40:30.476 --> 00:40:32.346 A:middle
Runs back.

00:40:33.036 --> 00:40:34.636 A:middle
Help! Oh, what am I
going to tell him?

00:40:35.006 --> 00:40:37.066 A:middle
I don't know if any super
heroes wear hearing aids,

00:40:37.066 --> 00:40:38.986 A:middle
and he can't know
his mom was lying!

00:40:40.096 --> 00:40:42.306 A:middle
But I have faith, I think
there are some, right?

00:40:42.306 --> 00:40:43.436 A:middle
I'm not a liar right?

00:40:43.786 --> 00:40:46.686 A:middle
So, there I am, and the
phone's ringing, like I said.

00:40:46.686 --> 00:40:47.946 A:middle
And I go to the meeting.

00:40:48.136 --> 00:40:53.116 A:middle
And my finger is going to the
delete button, and I stopped

00:40:53.456 --> 00:40:56.096 A:middle
and I said, what
would Peter Parker do?

00:40:58.156 --> 00:40:59.176 A:middle
Catholic guilt!

00:40:59.886 --> 00:41:02.206 A:middle
What would he do?

00:40:59.886 --> 00:41:02.206 A:middle
What would he do?

00:41:03.026 --> 00:41:04.806 A:middle
But that is seriously
something I would ask myself

00:41:04.806 --> 00:41:05.556 A:middle
when I was growing up.

00:41:05.556 --> 00:41:06.846 A:middle
I didn't really want
to be Spider-Man,

00:41:06.846 --> 00:41:07.926 A:middle
I wanted to be Peter Parker.

00:41:08.566 --> 00:41:11.246 A:middle
Because even though he wasn't
perfect, he always tried

00:41:11.246 --> 00:41:12.896 A:middle
to do the right thing.

00:41:13.676 --> 00:41:15.686 A:middle
So, I said, okay, power
and responsibility.

00:41:15.996 --> 00:41:16.586 A:middle
What can I do?

00:41:16.716 --> 00:41:17.886 A:middle
Well, I don't have
a lot of power,

00:41:17.886 --> 00:41:20.126 A:middle
but I have information
on super heroes.

00:41:20.126 --> 00:41:21.856 A:middle
And I have access to images.

00:41:21.856 --> 00:41:22.306 A:middle
I have that.

00:41:22.826 --> 00:41:23.846 A:middle
So, what's my responsibility?

00:41:23.846 --> 00:41:25.156 A:middle
I've got to use that
to help her.

00:41:25.706 --> 00:41:28.086 A:middle
So, instead of deleting the
email I sent it throughout

00:41:28.086 --> 00:41:29.306 A:middle
Marvel Editorial.

00:41:29.306 --> 00:41:30.216 A:middle
I said, what can we do?

00:41:31.016 --> 00:41:34.216 A:middle
Do we -- do you remember any
heroes that have hearing aids?

00:41:34.216 --> 00:41:35.906 A:middle
Or could we even maybe
ask one of our artists

00:41:35.906 --> 00:41:37.986 A:middle
to draw someone with
a hearing aid?

00:41:38.686 --> 00:41:41.056 A:middle
And my good friend Tom
Brevoort, who was my boss,

00:41:41.476 --> 00:41:42.766 A:middle
he reminded me of Hawkeye.

00:41:43.316 --> 00:41:44.636 A:middle
He said, oh, remember Hawkeye?

00:41:44.846 --> 00:41:45.496 A:middle
I said, you're right.

00:41:45.496 --> 00:41:48.436 A:middle
Back in the 80s he was on a
mission where he was trapped

00:41:48.436 --> 00:41:52.236 A:middle
by rubble and he used a sonic
arrow to get out of the rubble

00:41:52.276 --> 00:41:54.116 A:middle
and it burst his
eardrums and he was deaf.

00:41:54.516 --> 00:41:57.326 A:middle
And his good friend Tony
Stark, being the cool inventor

00:41:57.326 --> 00:41:59.126 A:middle
that he is, made
him hearing aids.

00:41:59.506 --> 00:42:02.026 A:middle
And to this day he's
our deaf hero.

00:41:59.506 --> 00:42:02.026 A:middle
And to this day he's
our deaf hero.

00:42:02.026 --> 00:42:04.486 A:middle
And we've done stories
about him either wanting

00:42:04.486 --> 00:42:05.676 A:middle
to wear his hearing aid or not.

00:42:05.676 --> 00:42:09.446 A:middle
We've done whole issues in
sign language to use him,

00:42:09.446 --> 00:42:12.356 A:middle
and to use him as a metaphor,
again to say that everyone can

00:42:12.356 --> 00:42:15.756 A:middle
and should be a hero, no matter
what your challenges may be.

00:42:16.016 --> 00:42:18.796 A:middle
So, I went through
our digital backlog

00:42:18.796 --> 00:42:20.796 A:middle
and I grabbed this
cover, because it was one

00:42:20.796 --> 00:42:22.116 A:middle
of my favorites when
I was growing up.

00:42:22.456 --> 00:42:24.496 A:middle
And I sent it to Christina
and I said, Christina,

00:42:24.686 --> 00:42:27.846 A:middle
I want you to show this
cover to Anthony and tell him

00:42:28.156 --> 00:42:30.996 A:middle
that not only do super heroes
wear hearing aids, but a member

00:42:30.996 --> 00:42:34.296 A:middle
of the world famous
Avengers wears a hearing aid.

00:42:34.476 --> 00:42:37.456 A:middle
And if Anthony wears his
hearing aid we will make him an

00:42:37.526 --> 00:42:38.506 A:middle
honorary Avenger.

00:42:39.546 --> 00:42:47.716 A:middle
And I thought, [applause] -- And
I thought, okay, good deed done

00:42:47.716 --> 00:42:50.196 A:middle
for the day, off
to my meeting I go.

00:42:51.896 --> 00:42:58.126 A:middle
The next Monday I get in my
in-box, this piece of art.

00:42:58.366 --> 00:43:01.206 A:middle
So, my friend Manny
Mederos, he saw my email,

00:42:58.366 --> 00:43:01.206 A:middle
So, my friend Manny
Mederos, he saw my email,

00:43:01.206 --> 00:43:02.636 A:middle
he knew I was sharing
the picture of Hawkeye.

00:43:03.146 --> 00:43:05.816 A:middle
He draws this, on his
own time, for free.

00:43:05.816 --> 00:43:06.896 A:middle
He draws this over the weekend.

00:43:07.406 --> 00:43:09.506 A:middle
He knew I sent the Hawkeye
cover, so he draws Hawkeye.

00:43:09.936 --> 00:43:12.586 A:middle
And then he invents Blue Ear

00:43:12.586 --> 00:43:14.856 A:middle
because that's what they
called the hearing aid.

00:43:15.676 --> 00:43:17.756 A:middle
And I send that to Christina.

00:43:18.326 --> 00:43:21.066 A:middle
And we -- I said, hey
man, that was awesome.

00:43:21.356 --> 00:43:22.806 A:middle
And we said, yeah, okay, cool.

00:43:23.456 --> 00:43:24.876 A:middle
Good deed done for the day.

00:43:24.916 --> 00:43:25.836 A:middle
We're done right?

00:43:26.276 --> 00:43:29.986 A:middle
No. Next day I get
this piece of art

00:43:29.986 --> 00:43:32.956 A:middle
by Nelson Ribeiro,
Adult Blue Ear!

00:43:33.716 --> 00:43:35.726 A:middle
With his mighty hearing
aid he's hearing trouble

00:43:35.726 --> 00:43:36.526 A:middle
and he will go help!

00:43:38.196 --> 00:43:43.166 A:middle
I send this to Christina and
we think, okay, we did it!

00:43:43.166 --> 00:43:43.706 A:middle
It's awesome!

00:43:47.056 --> 00:43:51.236 A:middle
Three weeks later she
writes me back and she says,

00:43:51.236 --> 00:43:55.136 A:middle
Bill you don't know
what an impact this had

